<h2>A Reimagined Story</h2>
<p>FNAF Rewritten '87 doesn't just retell the FNAF 2 story — it rewrites it entirely as part of a coherent trilogy. This is the second entry in the Rewritten saga, following the FNAF 1 remake, and the narrative threads connect directly.</p>

<p>The setup: after five children disappeared at the original Freddy Fazbear's Pizza, a massive corporation bought the franchise and built a new location with redesigned animatronics and upgraded security systems. You play as Jeremy Fitzgerald, a summer employee in 1987 who quickly realizes something is deeply wrong.</p>

<p>Between nights, cinematic cutscenes show the perspective of the child who possesses Freddy — from the moment of death through decades of existence trapped inside an animatronic. It's a haunting portrayal of what the "haunted robots" concept actually means for the souls inside them.</p>

<p>The Puppet takes on a far more complex role here. Rather than a straightforward villain, Charlie (the Puppet) is a grey antagonist — she gave the dead children life inside the animatronics and genuinely believes she's protecting them. She opposes anyone trying to uncover the truth because doing so would mean the children "truly die." The arcade minijuegos between nights show the souls' attempts at freedom while the Puppet works to keep them bound.</p>

<p>Night 6 shifts the perspective to Michael Afton, who infiltrates the pizzeria after the Bite of '87. Through Candy Cadet, it's confirmed that Michael has been the protagonist of the entire Rewritten saga. He endures hallucinations of William Afton blaming him for the Crying Child's death, and the night culminates in an intense escape sequence through the entire pizzeria, pursued by every animatronic. He escapes with Jeremy's logbook — a key item for the saga's conclusion.</p>

<h2>What the Community Says</h2>
<p>FNAF Rewritten '87 has earned near-universal praise, sitting at 4.8 out of 5 on itch.io with over 100 ratings.</p>

<p><strong>BNY</strong> called it <em>"the best FNAF 2 remake of these times, with astonishing quality"</em> and gave it an 8/10. He noted that it works as <em>"a 'what if' FNAF had its lore planned from day one"</em> and found it more enjoyable than the original. On the Night 6 escape sequence: <em>"It's scarier than anything the FNAF 2 movie tried to do."</em></p>

<p>Another reviewer highlighted the narrative as the game's greatest strength: <em>"Very few manage to give you a new and rewarding experience from already-known stories and mechanics."</em> He praised the real-time animations and the reworked Mangle and Toy Freddy mechanics specifically.</p>

<p><strong>Dexter White</strong> went further: <em>"This game is nothing short of a masterpiece."</em> He praised how it makes FNAF 2 feel like <em>"the overwhelming game Scott originally wanted it to be,"</em> calling the graphics, animations, and storytelling <em>"phenomenal."</em></p>

</div>

<div class="post-content">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
</div>

<div class="post-faq">
    <details>
        <summary>Is FNAF Rewritten '87 free?</summary>
        <div>Yes, it's completely free to download and play. The full game (version 2.2.2) is available as a single download.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>Do I need to play FNAF Rewritten 1 first?</summary>
        <div>It's recommended but not required. FNAF Rewritten '87 is the second entry in the Rewritten trilogy and builds on the first game's story, especially regarding Michael Afton's role. However, the game stands on its own as a FNAF 2 reimagining.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>How big is the download?</summary>
        <div>The full game is approximately 1.9 GB. There's also an older pre-Night 6 demo (1 GB), but the full release is recommended since it contains the complete experience including the Night 6 escape sequence.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>Is there a Custom Night?</summary>
        <div>No. Unlike the original FNAF 2, Rewritten '87 does not include a Custom Night or additional challenges. The developer focused on the 6-night story campaign and the explorable 3D environments instead.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>Is there an Android or Mac version?</summary>
        <div>No, FNAF Rewritten '87 is currently only available for Windows PC. There are no official plans for ports to other platforms.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>Will there be a third Rewritten game?</summary>
        <div>Yes. The trilogy will conclude with "Missing Children," which is planned for 2028. The original plan for 6 games was scrapped in favor of a tighter trilogy. The final entry will not include Elizabeth or the Funtime animatronics.</div>
    </details>
</div>

